Name: β Aqr
Notes:
Sadalsuud, Sadalsud, Sad es Saud, Sadalsund, Saad el Sund, Nir Saad al 
Saaoud, Lucida Fortunæ Fortunarum,[1] part of Saʽd al Suʽud;[2][3] triple 
star

Name: α Aqr
Notes:
Sadalmelik, Sadal Melik, Sadalmelek, Sadlamulk, El Melik, Saad el Melik, 
Ruchbah; double star

Name: ζ1 Aqr
Notes:
Sadaltager, Sadaltajir, Altager, Achr al Achbiya, Postrema Tabernaculorum,
[1] part of al Aḣbiyah;[4][5] binary star

Name: ε Aqr
Notes:
Albali, Al Bali, Nir Saad Bula, Lucida Fortunæ Dissipantis,[1] part of al 
Bulaʽ;[6][7] suspected variable

Name: γ Aqr
Notes:
Sadachbia, Sadalachbia, Aoul al Achbiya, Prima Tabernaculorum, part of al 
Aḣbiyah;[1][4][5] double star

Name: ζ2 Aqr
Notes: component of the ζ Aqr system

Name: ξ Aqr
Notes:
Bunda, Thanih Saad al Saaoud, Secunda Fortunæ Fortunarum,[1] part of Saʽd 
al Suʽud;[2][3] double star

Name: μ Aqr
Notes: Albulaan, part of al Bulaʽ;[6][7] double star, spectroscopic binary

Name: ο Aqr
Notes: Kae Uh; emission-line star; γ Cas variable, *V*max = 4.68m, *V*min = 4.89m

Name: π Aqr
Notes:
Seat, Wasat al Achbiya, Media Tabernaculorum, part of al Aḣbiyah;[1][4][5] 
emission-line star; γ Cas variable, *V*max = 4.42m, *V*min = 4.87m

Name: 108 Aqr
Notes:
ET Aqr; spectroscopic binary; α2 CVn variable, *V*max = 5.12m, *V*min = 5.21
m, *P* = 3.73524 d

Name: 74 Aqr
Notes: HI Aqr; double star; α2 CVn variable, Δ*V* = 0.01m, *P* = 3.4 d

Name: 70 Aqr
Notes:
FM Aqr; low-amplitude δ Sct variable, *V*max = 6.16m, *V*min = 6.19m, *P* = 
0.087 d

Name: 29 Aqr
Notes:
DX Aqr; triple star, spectroscopic binary; Algol variable, *V*max = 6.37m,

Name: 14 Aqr
Notes: IW Aqr; double star; semiregular variable, Δ*V* = ~0.07m, *P* = 163 d

Name: Gl 876
Notes:
IL Aqr; nearby red dwarf, BY Dra variable, *V*max = 10.15m, *V*min = 10.21m; 
has four planets (b, c, d & e)

Name: WASP-47
Notes: has four transiting planets (b, c, d & e)

Name: EZ Aqr
Notes: 12th closest star system; triple star; flare star
